Lecture Overview

The lecture today will continue Section 2.3 in Chapter 2 concerning continuous random variables, and will particularly focus on residence time distribution for chemical reactors. We will use all of the terms below, which we covered in previous lectures:

  • 2.3 Continuous Random Variables
    • 2.3 Cumulative Distribution Function, CDF: $F_X(x)=P(X \le x)$
    • 2.3.1 Expectation $E[X]$

Distribution of Residence Times for Chemical Reactors

  • In your studies so far in chemical reaction engineering, you will have developed models based on the assumption that the reactors have perfect mixing (i.e. ideal reactors)
  • In practice reactors are not perfectly mixed, so we need capture this behaviour: computing the Residence Time Distribution (RTD), represented as $\color{green}{E(t)}$, will be our method for doing so
  • Note that $\color{green}{E(t)}$ is a probability density function (PDF), and NOT the expectation operation, $E[T] = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} t \cdot f(t) \; dt$; but we'll use both here...
  • This is a topic you will cover in a lecture this term in Reaction Engineering I, and some of you will perform RTD experiments in 2nd Year Knowledge Laboratory.

  • The experimental approach to determining the residence time distribution (RTD) is conceptually simple: you inject an inert tracer into the chemical reactor, and then measure its concentration at the outlet of the reactor to determine the distribution of times that the tracer atoms have spent in the reactor.
  • Types of tracers: dyes, salt solutions (Knowledge Labs use KCl), radioactive material

Two injection methods for experimentally measuring RTD:

  • Pulse response - forms the basis for a PDF: $f(t) \propto \color{blue}{C(t)}$
  • Step response - forms the basis for a CDF: $F(t) \propto \color{blue}{C(t)}$

1. Pulse Response:

  • For $f(t)$ to be a valid PDF: $$\int_{-\infty}^{\infty} f(t) \; dt = \int_{0}^{\infty} f(t) \; dt = 1$$
  • Thus the PDF corresponding to the residence time distribution (denoted as $\color{green}{E(t)}$) is given by: $$\color{green}{E(t)} = f(t) = \frac{\color{blue}{C(t)}}{\color{red}{\int_{0}^{\infty} C(t) \; dt}}$$

2. Step Response:

  • Recall our definition of the cumulative distribution function (CDF): $$F(b) = \int_{-\infty}^{b} f(t) \; dt$$

  • Thus: \begin{align} F(t=-\infty) =F(t=0)&= 0 \\ F(t=\infty)&= 1 \end{align}

  • Applying the latter condition, we find that the residence time distribution $\color{green}{E(t)}$ can be computed from the CDF as: $$\color{green}{E(t)} = f(t) = \frac{dF(t)}{dt} = \frac{d}{dt} \frac{\color{blue}{C(t)}}{\color{red}{C_{0}}}$$

    • where $\color{red}{C_0}$ corresponds to tracer concentration at the step injection.

Using $E(t)$ to compute mean properties

  • Thus the PDF corresponding to the residence time distribution, $f(t) = \color{green}{E(t)}$, can experimentally measured from $\color{blue}{C(t)}$ by either a pulse or step injection experiment
  • We can also derive $\color{green}{E(t)}$ for ideal chemical reactors using first principles, which we will also do in this lecture
  • Once we have $\color{green}{E(t)}$, we can compute important quantities such as the mean residence time (denoted as $\overline t$) and mean concentration (denoted as $\overline C$) using the Expectation operation!

  • To compute these mean properties using the expectation, first recall that we defined expectation of a function $g(t)$ of random variable $t$ to be: $$E[g(T)] = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} g(t) \; f(t)\; dt$$

  • Noting that the PDF is $f(t)=\color{green}{E(t)}$ for random variable $t$ we have: \begin{align} \overline t &= E[T] = \cdots \\ \overline C &= E[C(T)] = \cdots \end{align}

Out[3]:

\begin{align} \overline t &= E[T] = \int_0^\infty t \cdot E[T] \; dt \\ \overline C &= E[C(T)] = \int_0^\infty C(t) \cdot E(t) \; dt \end{align}

Ideal CSTR

  • Ideal Mixing: what would $\color{green}{E(t)}$ be for an ideal CSTR?
  • A pulse tracer of concentration $C_0$ is added at time $t=0$. Assuming perfect mixing (concentration $\color{blue}{C(t)}$ at the outlet is equal to that within the reactor), the material balance around the CSTR for $t > 0$ is: $$\text{in + generation - out = accumulation} $$
In[4]:
display_answer(question=1, password='C0e^(-t/tau)')
Out[4]:

\begin{align} 0 &+ 0 -vC = V_R \frac{dC}{dt} \\ \frac{dC}{dt} &= \frac{-v}{V_R} C = - \frac{1}{\tau} C \\ \int_{C_0}^C \frac{dC}{C} &= - \frac{1}{\tau} \int_0^t \; dt \implies C(t) = C_0 \exp{\left(\frac{-t}{\tau}\right)} \\ \text{where tau is the "space time" or "holding time"} \end{align}

  • Ideal Mixing: what would $\color{green}{E(t)}$ be for an ideal CSTR?
  • For a pulse response, we defined the residence time distribution as: $$\color{green}{E(t)} = \frac{\color{blue}{C(t)}}{\color{red}{\int_{0}^{\infty} C(t) \; dt}} = \cdots$$
  • And so the mean residence time, for instance, is computed as: $$\overline t = E[T] = \cdots$$
In[5]:
display_answer(question=2, password='space time')
Out[5]:

\begin{align} \color{green}{E(t)} = \frac{\color{blue}{C(t)}}{\color{red}{\int_{0}^{\infty} C(t) \; dt}} &= \frac{C_0 \exp{\left(\frac{-t}{\tau}\right)}}{C_0 \int_0^\infty \exp{\left(\frac{-t}{\tau}\right)} \; dt} = \frac{\exp{\left(\frac{-t}{\tau}\right)}}{-\tau \left[ \exp{\left(\frac{-t}{\tau}\right)} \right]_0^\infty} = \frac{\exp{\left(\frac{-t}{\tau}\right)}}{\tau} \\ \overline t = E[T] &= \int_0^\infty t \cdot \frac{\exp{\left(\frac{-t}{\tau}\right)}}{\tau} \; dt \\ & \qquad \int u \; dv = uv - \int v \; du \\ & \qquad u = t \to du = 1 \\ & \qquad dv= \frac{\exp{\left(\frac{-t}{\tau}\right)}}{\tau} \to v = - \exp{\left(\frac{-t}{\tau}\right)} \\ &= \left[ -t \cdot \exp{\left(\frac{-t}{\tau}\right)} \right]_0^\infty + \int_0^\infty \exp{\left(\frac{-t}{\tau}\right)} \\ &= -\tau \left[ \exp{\left(\frac{-t}{\tau}\right)} \right]_0^\infty = \tau = \frac{V_R}{v} \end{align}

Non-Ideal CSTR: Lab Data

  • Consider a step-injection RTD experiment for a CSTR recently installed in the UG labs. The concentration of the KCl tracer is $\color{red}{C_{0}} = 0.055$ M.
  • The total volume of the CSTR reactor is $V_R=2.4$ L, filled to a level of 80%, with a flow rate of $v=1$ L/min.
  • The step response of KCl concentration ($\color{blue}{C(t)}$) is measured using a conductivity meter.
  • What is the corresponding space time?
In[6]:
display_answer(question=3, password='115.20')
Out[6]:

$$\tau = \frac{V_R}{v} = \frac{2.4 \text{ L} \times 0.8}{1 \text{ L/min}} \times \frac{60 \text{ s}}{\text{min}} = 115.20 \text{s}$$

mean_t = np.trapz(t*dCdt(t, *popt)/C0, t);

plt.axvline(mean_t, linestyle='--', label=r'$\overline{{t}}={:.2f}$ s'.format(mean_t), color='b')

Summary

This lecture continued our examples of continuous random variables (section 2.3), and introduced the concept of the residence time distribution (used in Knowledge Labs and RE-I):

  • The Residence Time Distribution, $\color{green}{E(t)}$, is a probability density function (PDF)

  • 1. Pulse Response: $\color{green}{E(t)}$ is computed by normalising $\color{blue}{C(t)}$: $$\color{green}{E(t)} = f(t) = \frac{\color{blue}{C(t)}}{\color{red}{\int_{0}^{\infty} C(t) \; dt}}$$

  • 2. Step Response: $\color{green}{E(t)}$ is computed as the derivative of $\color{blue}{C(t)}$ normalised by the magnitude of the step injection $\color{red}{C_{0}}$: $$\color{green}{E(t)} = f(t) = \frac{dF(t)}{dt} = \frac{d}{dt} \frac{\color{blue}{C(t)}}{\color{red}{C_{0}}}$$

  • Use expectation operation $E[g(T)]$ to get mean property values (e.g. residence time, concentration)
